    {
      "role": "user",
      "content": "hey i was reading a manual for a cessna and it mentioned the pitot tube. can u explain how it actually works to measure airspeed and why it's so important?",
      "source": "evaluator"
    },
    {
      "role": "assistant",
      "content": "The pitot tube is a crucial instrument for measuring airspeed, and it works by capturing the dynamic pressure of the air flowing over the aircraft. It's essentially a tiny, pointed opening that scoops up the air moving directly into the airstream. This pressure reading is then compared to the static air pressure, which is measured by a separate port, to calculate the difference—the dynamic pressure—which directly correlates to the aircraft's speed. It's vital because airspeed dictates how the wing generates lift, and without an accurate reading, flying is much more dangerous.",
      "source": "target",
